---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Contraflow Riding on One-Way Streets"
  year="2023"
  category="Urban Mobility · Safety Analysis"
  tools={['Python', 'GeoPandas', 'Shapely', 'QGIS', 'OpenStreetMap', 'Populus']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Overview</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        The Florentine neighborhood in south Tel Aviv is characterized by narrow, dense one-way streets —
        a common feature of older urban fabric built before the car. As shared e-scooter adoption grew
        rapidly across the city, anecdotal evidence and enforcement reports suggested riders were
        frequently traveling against designated traffic direction, raising serious safety concerns for
        both riders and other road users.
      </p>
      <p>
        This analysis used raw GPS trip data from the Populus mobility data platform to systematically
        identify scooter trips that conflicted with street directionality. Each recorded trip trajectory
        was overlaid against a street network derived from OpenStreetMap, with directional attributes
        assigned per segment. Spatial joins between trip routes and one-way segments allowed precise
        quantification of contraflow riding — by street, by time of day, and by operator.
      </p>
      <p>
        Results revealed significant contraflow concentration on specific corridors, providing actionable
        spatial intelligence for enforcement prioritization. The findings also informed infrastructure
        proposals: streets with the highest contraflow rates were cross-referenced with cycling
        infrastructure plans, identifying candidates for formal contra-flow bike lane designation.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Map — Florentine Contraflow Analysis</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/contraflow.png`}
      alt="Map showing contraflow e-scooter trips in the Florentine neighborhood, Tel Aviv"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Shared e-scooter trip segments classified as contraflow (against one-way direction) in the
      Florentine neighborhood, overlaid on the street network.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methods</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Trip GPS traces were matched to street segments using GeoPandas and Shapely geometric operations.
        Street directionality (oneway attributes) was extracted from OpenStreetMap and validated against
        municipal street data. A trip segment was classified as contraflow when its bearing conflicted
        with the permitted travel direction of the matched street segment by more than a defined angular
        threshold, filtering out GPS noise.
      </p>
      <p>
        Results were aggregated by street segment to produce a contraflow intensity surface, and by
        operator and time band to support operational recommendations. All analysis was conducted in
        Python with QGIS used for final cartographic output.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>
